http://t.co/WIFwT4ZXpk
@juhrman They still had to face some class suits, but were able to cope, and now they are worth a few billions
@juhrman They hired 500 students, got every client for a fix of the bug, and gave each and everyone of them a present and an apology
@juhrman They did the following: First, they allowed free calls for everyone (and this is 1995, costs to them, enormous) for a long time
@juhrman However, once they acknowledged their issue, the way they handled it made this history into a legend (ok, I am over telling)
@juhrman People got really angry at them, and they got a nick of Cellclum (in Hebrew, cellular nothing), and were about to go broke
@juhrman However, quite soon after they went on the air, a great network bug attacked them, caused by a bad supplier (motorola)
@juhrman they had great pricing, and great offering at the time and were opposing a monopoly (see your own similarities)
@juhrman (This will come in a few tweets). In 1995, a new cellular operator named Cellcom started working in Israel.
@juhrman A backer with no ouya here, I have a good history lesson for you on how to solve your issue and thrive, LMK if you want to hear.
